## Description
A flaw exists within (de)seralization functionality within XStream. Sending a carefully crafted object data will crash the Java process and cause a DoS *(Denial of Service)*. In order to exploit this vulnerability, users require the ability to manipulate the incoming stream of data.

## Vulnerabilities(BDSA,CVE)
:yellow_circle: [CVE-2017-7957](https://openhub.net/vulnerabilities/bdsa/CVE-2017-7957) - Weak Input Validation



## Solution
Upgrade to version **1.4.10** or later.

## Workaround
XStream contains since version 1.4.7 a security framework to prevent an 
attack described in CVE-2013-7285. This framework can also be used to 
suppress the current vulnerability by setting:

xstream.denyTypes(void.class, Void.class);

Users of older XStream releases can register an own converter for the 'void' 
type, that also protects against this attack:

xstream.registerConverter(new Converter() {
  public boolean canConvert(Class type) {
    return Void.class == type || void.class == type;
  }
  public Object unmarshal(HierarchicalStreamReader reader, 
UnmarshallingContext context) {
    throw new ConversionException("Type void cannot have an instance");
  }
  public void marshal(Object source, HierarchicalStreamWriter writer, 
MarshallingContext context) {
    throw new ConversionException("Type void cannot have an instance");
  }
}, XStream.PRIORITY_VERY_HIGH);



